INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Email Subject Lines', 'email-subject-lines', '<h2>Email Subject Lines</h2>
<p>When writing subject lines for emails, clarity and descriptiveness are key to ensure recipients understand the purpose and urgency of the message at a glance.</p>
<blockquote><p><strong>In a nutshell, just get to the point!</strong></p></blockquote>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: "Wow, straight to the point" meme — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<ul>
<li>Summarize the main topic or action required in a concise manner.</li>
<li>Avoid vague or ambiguous subject lines that may cause confusion or lead to the email being overlooked.</li>
<li>Consider including relevant keywords to convey the primary focus of the email and compel recipients to open it promptly.</li>
<li>Use specific details or deadlines when applicable to provide context and urgency.</li>
</ul>
<blockquote><p>By prioritizing clear and descriptive subject lines, senders can enhance the effectiveness of their emails, improve recipient engagement, and streamline communication within the organization.</p></blockquote>', 41, TRUE, 2
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Email Structure', 'email-structure', '<h2>Email Structure</h2>
<blockquote><p><em>Effective email structure ensures <strong>clarity, professionalism, and readability.</strong></em></p></blockquote>
<ol>
<li><strong>Begin</strong> with a clear and appropriate greeting or salutation, addressing the recipient by name if possible to personalize the communication.</li>
<li>In the <strong>body</strong> of the email, organize your thoughts logically with proper paragraphing and use bullet points or numbered lists for conveying information concisely, especially for complex topics or action items.</li>
<li>When <strong>closing</strong> the email, include a courteous sign-off such as "Best regards" or "Sincerely," followed by your name and any relevant contact information or job title. Consider adding a professional email signature containing your name, position, company, and contact details to provide recipients with additional context and facilitate further communication.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote><p>Adhering to these best practices for email structure helps ensure that your messages are well-organized, easy to read, and effectively convey the intended message to recipients.</p></blockquote>', 42, TRUE, 2
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Email Threads', 'email-threads', '<h2>Email Threads</h2>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Email Threads video tutorial — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>When you''re diving into writing emails, stick to what the convo is all about. Veering off into the wild blue yonder can really throw everyone for a loop and muddle up what we''re all trying to get at. Keeping our eyes on the prize, or rather, the topic, helps everyone stay on the same page and chip in their two cents way more effectively.</p>
<blockquote><p><strong>Not everyone needs to see your reply.</strong></p></blockquote>
<p>Before you bring everyone into the mix, think about who really needs to be in on the convo. This way, you''re not clogging up inboxes or causing any head-scratching moments.</p>
<p>When managing an email thread, ensure all relevant parties are included to foster great teamwork and cover all perspectives. It''s essential to reply specifically to <strong>only</strong> those who need the information to avoid overwhelming others with unnecessary details.</p>
<p>If someone''s wrapped up a topic with a neat little bow, there''s no need to pile on with a "Thanks for the update" unless it really adds something. <strong>Let''s keep our email chats sharp and concise.</strong></p>
<h3>Email threads:</h3>
<ul>
<li>Don''t go off topic, stay on subject in the thread</li>
<li>Don''t assume "reply all" is necessary.</li>
<li>Consider the involvement of all parties.</li>
<li>Reply to only relevant parties.</li>
<li>Consider not sending pleasantries if the previous email has a conclusive tone.</li>
<li>It''s not always necessary to send something like, "Thanks for the update".</li>
</ul>
<h3>Using "@":</h3>
<ul>
<li>Not acceptable as an introduction.</li>
<li>Not acceptable when addressing a customer; always address customers respectfully.</li>
<li>Only acceptable when highlighting an action item for a team member.</li>
</ul>', 43, TRUE, 3
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Using @ in Emails', 'email-using-at-sign', '<h2>Using @ in Emails</h2>
<blockquote><p><em>So, about using "@" in our emails, we gotta know when and how to use it correctly.</em></p></blockquote>
<p>Throwing "@" into the mix is perfect when you wanna flag an <strong>action item</strong> for a specific team member. It''s like saying, "Hey, check this out!" or "This one''s on you!" It helps everyone zero in on what they gotta do, making sure nothing slips through the cracks.</p>
<p><strong>BUT</strong>, and it''s a big BUT, rolling into an email with "@" right off the bat? Not the best move.</p>
<p>And when it comes to chatting with customers or the folks outside our little world, let''s keep "@" out of it. We wanna make sure we''re always coming across as the respectful and polished pros we are.</p>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Email Policy — Using "@" video tutorial — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>', 44, TRUE, 2
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Timely Responses', 'email-timely-responses', '<h2>Timely Responses</h2>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: "Still Waiting" meme — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>Getting back to emails on time is pretty much the golden rule if you want to keep things running smoothly and make sure everyone''s on the same page.</p>
<blockquote><p><strong>The general rule is to respond within a day or two, tops, unless there''s a really good reason you can''t.</strong></p></blockquote>
<p>If for some reason, you can''t dive into a full reply right away, it''s totally OK to just drop a quick note saying, "Got your email! Thanks, and I''ll get back to you soon." It''s like giving a virtual high five, letting them know you''re on it. It keeps the trust tank full and shows you''ve got your act together.</p>
<blockquote><p>And for those times when you''re swamped or out of the office, setting up an auto-reply is a lifesaver.</p></blockquote>
<p>If a message needs more brainpower or time than you''ve got right at that moment, a heads-up to the sender with a "Hey, I need a bit more time but haven''t forgotten you!" can work wonders. It''s all about keeping that conversation flowing and making sure no one''s left hanging.</p>', 45, TRUE, 2
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Handling Different Types of Email Inquiries', 'email-handling-different-types', '<h2>Handling Different Types of Email Inquiries</h2>
<p>When you''re juggling all sorts of emails, whether they''re just folks asking questions or needing a bit more from you, it''s super important to keep calm and stay sharp.</p>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: "Everybody just chill, just relax" meme — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<h3>Respond to simple inquiries quickly and clearly.</h3>
<p>For complex emails, acknowledge receipt immediately and estimate a response time, involving team members as necessary.</p>
<p>Empathize with customer complaints, apologize if needed, and take action to resolve issues, ensuring satisfaction.</p>
<p>Handle confidential information with care, adhering to company policies.</p>
<blockquote><p><strong>Effective email communication is crucial for maintaining professional relationships and solving problems.</strong></p></blockquote>', 46, TRUE, 3
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Why Do We Need a Conflict Policy?', 'conflict-policy-why-we-need-it', '<h2>Why Do We Need a Conflict Policy?</h2>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Conflict Policy Intro video thumbnail — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<blockquote><p><strong>We emphasize open communication, teamwork, and respect to maintain a positive workplace.</strong></p></blockquote>
<p>Our approach involves cheering each other on, listening, and resolving issues through dialogue or with supervisor assistance if needed. We handle conflicts with both informal chats and formal steps, ensuring fair resolutions, possibly including training or other corrective measures, with ongoing check-ins.</p>
<p>We aim to keep our workplace innovative and welcoming. Let''s work together to maintain a positive environment!</p>', 47, TRUE, 3
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Reasons for Interpersonal Conflict', 'conflict-reasons-for-interpersonal-conflict', '<h2>Reasons for Interpersonal Conflict</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Poor Communication</strong>
<ul>
<li>Open and transparent communication between all levels of the organization.</li>
<li>Active listening.</li>
<li>Do not make assumptions</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Personality/Value Clashes</strong>
<ul>
<li>Embrace diversity and inclusion.</li>
<li>Respect individual differences.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Lack of Resources</strong>
<ul>
<li>Transparent resource allocation.</li>
<li>Collaboration and sharing of resources.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Poorly Defined Roles</strong>
<ul>
<li>Well-defined job descriptions and responsibilities.</li>
<li>Clear channels for communication and coordination.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>', 48, TRUE, 3
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Common Types of Interpersonal Conflict', 'conflict-common-types', '<h2>Common Types of Interpersonal Conflict</h2>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Two people arguing scene — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<ol>
<li><strong>Pseudo Conflict</strong> – Two people agree but think they don''t. Created by poor communication and assumptions.</li>
<li><strong>Fact Conflict</strong> – Two or more disagree about the facts of a topic or situation.</li>
<li><strong>Policy Conflict</strong> – A dispute over a course of action based on a policy or company guidelines.</li>
<li><strong>Value Conflict</strong> – An employee''s personal values do not align with company values. Or an individual''s values conflict with their coworkers.</li>
<li><strong>Ego Conflict</strong> – An individual takes everything personally.</li>
<li><strong>Meta Conflict</strong> – A disagreement about how a conflict is being handled or resolved. Essentially, a conflict about a conflict.</li>
</ol>', 49, TRUE, 3
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Approaches to Conflict Resolution', 'conflict-approaches-to-resolution', '<h2>Approaches to Conflict Resolution</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Collaborative</strong> – Both parties work together to find a resolution.</li>
<li><strong>Compromise</strong> – Both parties find balance and get some of what they want while both also make concessions.</li>
<li><strong>Accommodation</strong> – One party is willing to allow the other party to have what they want.</li>
</ol>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Dos and Don''ts for Workplace Conflict YouTube video — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>', 50, TRUE, 2
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Conflict Resolution Strategies', 'conflict-resolution-strategies', '<h2>Conflict Resolution Strategies</h2>
<ol>
<li>Set Ground Rules</li>
<li>Active Listening</li>
<li>Face-to-Face Meetings</li>
<li>Avoid Making It Personal</li>
</ol>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: How to Resolve Conflict in the Workplace YouTube video — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>', 51, TRUE, 2
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Conflict Mediation', 'conflict-mediation', '<h2>Conflict Mediation</h2>
<blockquote><p><em>If a conflict cannot be resolved between two individuals, management-lead mediation may be necessary.</em></p></blockquote>
<h3>This mediation may include, but is not limited to:</h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>Individual Meetings:</strong> Separate meetings with each party to understand perspectives with open and honest discussions.</li>
<li><strong>Joint Exploration:</strong> Joint meetings with all involved parties with established boundaries.</li>
<li><strong>Negotiation:</strong> Collaborative problem-solving by identifying common ground and working towards a win-win solution.</li>
</ol>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: How Does Workplace Mediation Work? YouTube video — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>', 52, TRUE, 3
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Conflict Policy: Conclusion', 'conflict-policy-conclusion', '<h2>Conflict Policy: Conclusion</h2>
<blockquote><p><em>If individual team members are unable to resolve a conflict on their own, it is their responsibility to report the conflict to their supervisor for resolution assistance.</em></p></blockquote>
<p>Management-lead conflict resolution will utilize the approaches and strategies outlined in this guide. If management-lead mediation is unable to resolve the conflict, management may seek mediation via a third-party mediator.</p>
<blockquote><p><strong>Innovative Air Technologies is dedicated to cultivating a workplace where employees can thrive in a positive and respectful atmosphere.</strong></p></blockquote>
<p>This conflict resolution policy serves as a guide to proactively address conflicts, promote open communication, and uphold the well-being of our employees, contributing to the overall success of our organization.</p>
<blockquote><p><strong><em>Together</em>, we strive to maintain a workplace characterized by collaboration, innovation, and mutual respect.</strong></p></blockquote>', 53, TRUE, 2
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Understanding Our Discipline Policy', 'discipline-policy-overview', '<h2>Understanding Our Discipline Policy</h2>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Understanding Discipline Policy in Our Company video thumbnail — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>At Innovative Air Technologies, our mission is to foster a workplace built on respect, integrity, and collaboration. Our Discipline Policy serves as a framework to ensure consistency, fairness, and accountability in addressing behavior or performance issues that do not align with our core values or expectations.</p>
<p>This policy is designed not just to enforce standards but to provide employees with clear opportunities to learn, improve and succeed. By working together to address challenges constructively, we aim to maintain a positive, productive environment where everyone can thrive.</p>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: "Behave yourself" meme — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>', 54, TRUE, 3
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Grounds for Disciplinary Action', 'discipline-grounds-for-action', '<h2>Grounds for Disciplinary Action</h2>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Grounds for Disciplinary Action Review video thumbnail — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>At Innovative Air Technologies, we''ve got a clear guide that lays out what could get you in hot water, discipline-wise. It''s like a roadmap showing you the do''s and don''ts to help you steer clear of trouble. This list is not comprehensive; rather, it is examples of the types of conduct that this company does not tolerate.</p>
<h3>Examples of behavior that may lead to disciplinary measures:</h3>
<ul>
<li>Engaging in acts of discrimination or harassment in the workplace.</li>
<li>Possessing, distributing or being under the influence of illicit controlled substances.</li>
<li>Being under the influence of a controlled substance or alcohol at work, on company premises, or while engaged in company business.</li>
<li>Unauthorized use of company property, equipment, devices, or assets.</li>
<li>Damage, destruction or theft of company property, equipment, devices, or assets.</li>
<li>Removing company property without prior authorization or disseminating company information without authorization.</li>
<li>Falsification, misrepresentation or omission of company information, documents, or records.</li>
<li>Lying, associated to issues pertaining to company business and policies</li>
<li>Insubordination or refusal to comply with directives.</li>
<li>Failing to adequately perform job responsibilities.</li>
<li>Excessive or unexcused absenteeism or tardiness.</li>
<li>Disclosing confidential or proprietary company information without permission.</li>
<li>Illegal or violent activity, on company property or during company business</li>
<li>Falsifying injury reports or reasons for leave.</li>
<li>Possessing unauthorized weapons on premises.</li>
<li>Disregard for safety and security procedures.</li>
<li>Disparaging or disrespecting supervisors and/or co-workers.</li>
<li>Gossip.</li>
<li>Any other action or conduct that is inconsistent with company policies, procedures, values, or expectations.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Just a heads-up,</strong> the list isn''t the be-all and end-all. It doesn''t cover every single thing that could land you in hot water. We get that every situation is its own beast, so we promise to look at things on a case-by-case basis, weighing up what happened and how serious it is before deciding on any disciplinary action.</p>', 55, TRUE, 4
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Disciplinary Procedures', 'discipline-procedures', '<h2>Disciplinary Procedures</h2>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Disciplinary Procedures video thumbnail — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>The below steps are typically taken to handle all disciplinary actions of the company. Evaluation of each infraction by the manager or supervisor determines the steps taken.</p>
<ol>
<li>Step 1: Verbal Warning/Counseling</li>
<li>Step 2: Written Warning</li>
<li>Step 3: Employee Suspension</li>
<li>Step 4: Termination</li>
</ol>
<h3>Step 1: Verbal Warning/Counseling</h3>
<p>Manager will have a conversation with the employee regarding the facts of the infraction, the seriousness of the incident and finally the company''s expectation that the employee will not repeat said infraction in the future. This conversation is intended to help the employee understand how their behaviors need to change. The infraction will be documented in the employee''s file and be subject to review during performance evaluations.</p>
<h3>Step 2: Written Warning</h3>
<p>Manager will have a follow-up conversation along with a formal, written warning. The written warning will include a description of the infraction, along with the manager''s expectation of the employee''s behavior, description of the consequences if the expectations are not met, and a time frame for meeting expectations. The formal written warning will be signed by the employee and manager that the conversation took place; this not meant as an admission of guilt. A copy will be given to the employee for his/her record.</p>
<h3>Step 3: Employee Suspension and Improvement Plan</h3>
<p>Manager to document infraction and discuss with employee. The employee is then escorted to leave the premise and not return until suspension has ended. Upon return an action plan will be put in place to correct the behavior and prevent recurrences. Failure to follow will result in immediate termination.</p>
<h3>Step 4: Termination</h3>
<p>Manager to document infraction and discuss with employee. The employee is then escorted to gather personal items prior to leaving the premises — any unruly behavior forfeits this. Upon termination, an employee is required to:</p>
<ol>
<li>Turn in all reports and paperwork required to be completed by the employee when due and no later than the last day of work.</li>
<li>Return all files, documents, equipment, keys, access cards, software or other property belonging to the company that are in the employee''s possession, custody or control, and turn in all passwords to his/her supervisor.</li>
</ol>', 56, TRUE, 4
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Discipline Policy Enforcement', 'discipline-policy-enforcement', '<h2>Discipline Policy Enforcement</h2>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Understanding Discipline Policy Enforcement video thumbnail — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>A 30-day virtual clock will start with each different infraction. If a repeat infraction of the same rule is committed in that time period the following steps will be taken and the clock will restart with each infraction. After 30 days with no infractions, the clock expires.</p>
<p>With each additional infraction the level of discipline increases up to and including termination.</p>
<p>All infractions are logged in the employee''s file.</p>
<ul>
<li>Minor infractions (ex: tardy, disregard for safety) will start 30-day virtual clock.</li>
<li>Major infractions (ex: theft, drugs, destruction, lying, insubordination) will be immediately assessed by manager.</li>
</ul>', 57, TRUE, 3
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
