SELECT m.id, 'Mechanical Design Procedure – 001', 'mechanical-design-procedure-001', '<h2>Mechanical Design Procedure – 001</h2><p>This document defines the standardized procedure for transitioning engineered concepts into production-ready design packages. Its purpose is to ensure accuracy, consistency, and cross-functional alignment from initial project release through final build documentation.</p><p>The Engineering Production Design process establishes clear checkpoints for scope validation, drawing development, internal review, procurement coordination, and final documentation approval. By following this procedure, we minimize rework, control risk, maintain quality standards, and ensure every project is released to operations with a complete and build-ready package.</p><p>All team members involved in engineering, drafting, purchasing, and operations are expected to follow this process to maintain efficiency, accountability, and technical integrity across every job.</p><ol><li><em>Purpose</em><ol type="a"><li>To show the production design phase process for IAT DH units.</li></ol></li><li><em>Scope</em><ol type="a"><li>Compact, Rotor Series and IDP Units.</li></ol></li><li><em>Responsibility</em><ol type="a"><li>Engineering</li></ol></li><li><em>References</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Definitions</em><ol type="a"><li>IDP – Integrated Desiccant Product</li><li>LLI – Long-Lead Items</li><li>DH – Dehumidifier</li><li>Takt Time – Cycle Time</li><li>Total Time – Total Project Duration</li></ol></li><li><em>Safety</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Procedure</em></li></ol><h3>Procedure Checklist</h3><ol><li><strong>Open engineering takt time form</strong></li><li><strong>Print design check list</strong><ol type="a"><li>File location</li></ol></li><li><strong>Print approved submittal package</strong><ol type="a"><li>Print customer notes, if approved as noted.</li><li>Print additional customer specification or design notes received by email.</li><li>Print sales order.</li><li>Print LLI cutsheets.</li></ol></li><li><strong>Review all project info for discrepancies.</strong><ol type="a"><li>If errors or discrepancies exist, contact source for clarification.</li><li>Once all project info had been verified, continue to next step.</li></ol></li><li><strong>Open and print mechanical/structural design checklist.</strong><ol type="a"><li>Check-off items as the project progresses. Don&apos;t not wait until the very end to complete.</li></ol></li><li><strong>Open build package template in job folder.</strong><ol type="a"><li>Rename with file name.</li><li>Fill out build package with main features similar to template.</li></ol></li><li><strong>Begin design of DH</strong> (NOTE: Always remember to &ldquo;save all&rdquo; often in SolidWorks to save yourself the common pain of SolidWorks crashing!)</li><li><strong>Is unit a compact?</strong></li><li><strong>Is unit a rotor series?</strong><ol type="a"><li>Does master exist?</li><li>Is master up to current design standards?</li></ol></li><li><strong>Is unit an IDP?</strong><ol type="a"><li>Does a master exist? (Typically, no)</li><li><strong>Is there a similar job worth copying from?</strong><ol><li>If not, create from scratch.</li><li>If yes, open assembly and rename with new job number.<ol><li>Create text file in build package area stating job that it was copied from for future reference.</li></ol></li></ol></li><li><strong>Match overall DIM with overall DIM stated in the approved Submittal package.</strong></li><li>Drop in all LLI and purchased parts into assembly.<ol><li>Refer to flow diagram for integrating placement into the design. Use the tip-over rule for placement.</li></ol></li><li>If gas burners exist, go to gas burner selection.<ol><li>File Location: C:\Users\James Pope\Dropbox (Team IAT)\IAT\IAT CADLibrary\03-General\Heaters\Gas Burners\Direct Fired Selection Tool</li><li>Select burner size from BTUH values in green range.</li></ol></li><li>Create/modify sheet metal parts.<ol><li>Add text (etching lines) to split skins. Typically inner floor, outer floor, and all wall skins. Use numeric system for identifying parts.</li></ol></li><li>Create/modify framing.</li><li>Create/modify skid. (The skid may need to be sent out for vendor fabrication prior to production release. Verify with scheduler when commencing design.)<ol><li>Is skid 3&quot; channel? If so, design according to tube laser services standards.</li><li>Is skid 5&quot; channel? If so, design according to tube laser service standards.</li><li>Is skid 6&quot; channel or larger? Tube laser vendor may not be able to handle the larger size.<ol><li>If using tube laser service, design according to vendor standards.</li><li>If not using tube laser service, create skid to be cut. Send to vendor to quote when skid drawings are complete. (Example: Ryerson)</li><li>Do not design for cutting in house unless specified from manufacturing. (Discuss with GM)</li></ol></li><li>Add lifting lugs as required.<ol><li>Verify load does not exceed capacity of lifting lugs. (Example: Double reinforced lifting lugs were checked by SolidWorks Fea at 3000lbs max per lifting point.)</li><li>Add splits as required.<ol><li>Note: When using outside vendors, confirm max member length to determine if shipping splits are required or not.</li></ol></li></ol></li></ol></li><li>Create display states.<ol><li>Outside view. All parts unhidden. Juan hidden.</li><li>Submittal view. All parts unhidden. Juan unhidden.</li><li>Inside view. Hide all outer skins and doors.</li><li>Doors hidden views. Set door to transparent.</li><li>When design is complete, double check design for interference and hole alignment.</li></ol></li></ol></li><li><strong>Schedule pre production design review.</strong><ol type="a"><li>Include fabrication lead, fabricator, CNC, and electrician.</li><li>CC GM and scheduler.</li><li>Limit meeting to 30 minutes for slightly modified design and 1 hour for larger complex units.</li><li>Record comments from meeting and update drawings accordingly.</li></ol></li><li><strong>Create/compile documents for production release.</strong><ol type="a"><li><strong>Update unit outline with latest changes.</strong><ol><li>Add as-built label to drawings.</li><li>Send to customer.</li></ol></li><li><strong>Create IOM.</strong><ol><li>Open IOM for master location.</li><li>Save in IOM folder in the job file.</li><li>Delete instructions on components that do not exist in the design.</li><li>Add plan view of unit with working clearances.</li><li>Update filter sizes and quantities.</li></ol></li><li><strong>Create eDrawing.</strong><ol><li>Save as top level assembly as an eDrawing in the job folder.</li></ol></li><li><strong>Create framing drawings.</strong><ol><li>1st page ISO view.<ol><li>Add part balloons.</li><li>Add weldment cut list. (Top right of drawing.)</li></ol></li><li>2nd page front, rear, top, BTM, LH, RH views.<ol><li>Add part balloons.</li><li>Add dim.<ol><li>Start 0.0 top LH corner of framing.</li><li>Dim to framing as shown in figure below.</li></ol></li></ol></li><li>Save weldment cut list as an excel file.<ol><li>Match formatting exactly to the formatting required by TigerStop.<ol><li>Save as a CSV file.</li><li>Send to TigerStop folder.</li><li>Tiger files should create automatically.</li><li>If not, verify formatting in CSV file is correct.</li></ol></li><li>Calculate sticks of framing and quantity of joints from Excel file.</li><li>Compile framing drawings and TigerStop files and send to manufacturing and inventory dept.<ol><li>Add quantity of framing and joints required to email.</li></ol></li></ol></li></ol></li><li><strong>Create step files for skid only if sending for tube laser services.</strong><ol><li>File name is the part description [Job#]-[Item#]-[Shape]-[Material]-[Quantity]-[Length in inches]</li><li>Example: 2615-1-C5x6.7-A36-QTY3-75.000L</li></ol></li><li><strong>Create skid drawings if cutting in-house or using pre-cut lengths.</strong><ol><li>Skid drawings typically not required for tube laser skids.</li><li>Send skid drawings to manufacturing if they exist.</li></ol></li><li><strong>Create derived configuration for sheet metal parts only.</strong><ol><li>Suppress all parts that are not sheet metal.</li><li>Create step file.</li><li>Compile step file and another sheet metal files and send to CNC operator.<ol><li>CC shop lead, GM, EM and scheduler.</li></ol></li></ol></li></ol></li><li><strong>Complete mechanical/structural design checklist.</strong><ol type="a"><li>Sign document.</li><li>Scan and in job folder build package.</li></ol></li><li><strong>Send production release.</strong><ol type="a"><li>Subject: Production drawings released for job#(XXXX)</li><li>Body: Attached are the production released drawings. Remember to refer to the build package for additional project requirements. Thanks!</li><li>Include attachments: eDrawing, Unit Outline, Electrical Drawings, and Build Package Notes.</li></ol></li><li><strong>Update BOM (Process to be created)</strong></li><li><strong>Create IOM.</strong><ol type="a"><li>Save in the IOM folder in the job file.</li></ol></li><li><strong>Enter Takt Time completion date.</strong></li><li><strong>Process complete.</strong></li></ol>', 55, TRUE, 10
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'engineering'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Job Purchase Order Procedure – 007', 'job-purchase-order-procedure-007', '<h2>Job Purchase Order Procedure – 007</h2><p><em>Step-by-step process for creating, tracking, and completing purchase orders for job-related materials.</em></p><ol><li><em>Purpose</em><ol type="a"><li>To train engineers on how to select EZ Coils.</li></ol></li><li><em>Scope</em><ol type="a"><li>EZ Coil Selection</li></ol></li><li><em>Responsibility</em><ol type="a"><li>Engineering</li></ol></li><li><em>References</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Definitions</em><ol type="a"><li>IDP – Integrated Desiccant Product</li><li>LLI – Long-Lead Items</li><li>DH – Dehumidifier</li><li>Takt Time – Cycle Time</li><li>Total Time – Total Project Duration</li></ol></li><li><em>Safety</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Procedure</em></li></ol><h3>Job Purchase Order Procedure</h3><ol><li><strong>Create new PO in QB</strong></li><li><strong>Add any additional standard notes in the body of the PO (ex: Coilmaster, etc.)</strong></li><li><strong>Reminders</strong><ol type="a"><li>Make a new IAT item # if one does not exist for what you are ordering.</li><li>Enter job under customer column</li><li>Enter job number in the memo field.</li></ol></li><li><strong>Email to the vendor and attach any quotes to the email prior to sending.</strong><ol type="a"><li>Confirm the email was sent through QB.</li></ol></li><li><strong>Add the PO to the Open PO List in the Master Excel spreadsheet.</strong></li><li><strong>Add ship date received from order acknowledgement to the Open PO list.</strong><ol type="a"><li>Follow-up every other day until acknowledgement/ship date is received.</li></ol></li><li><strong>Follow-up on the PO weekly until received.</strong><ol type="a"><li>Add follow-up notes to the Open PO list.</li></ol></li><li><strong>Once received, add the received date to the Open PO list.</strong><ol type="a"><li>If only partial received, add date in the notes column on the Open PO list (ex: partial 11/20/22)</li><li>Repeat #7 and #8 until received in full.</li></ol></li></ol>', 56, TRUE, 4
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'engineering'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Unit Released for Shipment Protocol – 009', 'unit-released-for-shipment-protocol-009', '<h2>Unit Released for Shipment Protocol – 009</h2><p><em>Step-by-step process for creating, tracking, and completing purchase orders for job-related materials.</em></p><ol><li><em>Purpose</em><ol type="a"><li>To train engineers on prepping units for shipment.</li></ol></li><li><em>Scope</em><ol type="a"><li>Shipment Protocol</li></ol></li><li><em>Responsibility</em><ol type="a"><li>Engineering</li></ol></li><li><em>References</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Definitions</em><ol type="a"><li>IDP – Integrated Desiccant Product</li><li>LLI – Long-Lead Items</li><li>DH – Dehumidifier</li><li>Takt Time – Cycle Time</li><li>Total Time – Total Project Duration</li></ol></li><li><em>Safety</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Procedure</em></li></ol><h3>Unit Released for Shipment Protocol</h3><ol><li><strong>Payment</strong><ol type="a"><li>Has the customer paid the amount due prior to shipment?<ol><li>Get with Crystal if needed</li><li>Unit is not released for shipment until paid</li></ol></li><li>Will IAT Invoice? Net term</li></ol></li><li><strong>Special</strong><ol type="a"><li>Any special notes like waiting on submitting approval?</li><li>Loose items shipping with unit</li><li>UL unit</li><li>Note: get with Crystal if needed</li></ol></li><li><strong>Shipment</strong><ol type="a"><li>Flatbed or LTL</li><li>Is the freight by Customer?</li><li>Is the freight by IAT?</li><li>Look for as built drawings in the IOM folder in the job file<ol><li>As build drawings are not in the job folder.</li><li>Ask James for the as built drawing.</li></ol></li><li>Note: arrange accordingly.</li></ol></li></ol>', 57, TRUE, 4
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'engineering'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Control Box Selection Procedure – 011', 'control-box-selection-procedure-011', '<h2>Control Box Selection Procedure – 011</h2><p><em>Step-by-step process for creating, tracking, and completing purchase orders for job-related materials.</em></p><ol><li><em>Purpose</em><ol type="a"><li>To instruct IAT Team Members on the Control Box Selection Process</li></ol></li><li><em>Scope</em><ol type="a"><li>All Control Boxes</li></ol></li><li><em>Responsibility</em><ol type="a"><li>Electrical Engineer</li><li>Electrician or Electrical Team Lead</li><li>CAD Designer</li></ol></li><li><em>References</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Definitions</em><ol type="a"><li>BOM – Bill of Materials</li><li>EE – Electrical Engineer</li></ol></li><li><em>Safety</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Procedure</em></li></ol><h3>Control Box Selection Procedure</h3><ol><li><strong>Prior to Electrical Drawing and BOM release to production, Electrical Engineer is to verify whether a control box and panel needs to be selected and sized for the application or not.</strong><ol type="a"><li>If a control box and panel are not required.</li><li>If a control box and panel have already been selected, verify with the Electrical Team Lead that the control box and panel are the correct size.<ol><li>If size is good, proceed to step 7.5</li><li>If size is incorrect, Electrical Team Lead must size new control box and panel, go to step 7.2.</li><li>If a control box and panel need to be sized and selected, the Electrical Engineer is to notify the Electrician or Electrical Team Lead by email that a control box needs to be sized and selected.</li></ol></li></ol></li><li><strong>After the Electrician or Electrical Team Lead have selected the control box, the team member is to send an email to the Electrical Engineer on the size selected.</strong></li><li><strong>If the control box and panel are to be purchased, the EE is to complete the following:</strong><ol type="a"><li>Source a supplier (Saginaw is preferred)</li><li>Add the Control Box and Control Panel to the Elec BOM tab in the BOM worksheet.</li><li>Notify CAD Designer of size selected.</li></ol></li><li><strong>If the control box and panel are to be made in house, the EE is to notify the CAD Designer of any changes to the size or orientation of the panel.</strong></li><li><strong>After parts have been entered to the BOM the Electrical Drawings &amp; Bom are ready for Production Release.</strong></li><li><strong>Process Complete.</strong></li></ol>', 58, TRUE, 4
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'engineering'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'EZ Coil Selection Procedure – 012', 'ez-coil-selection-procedure-012', '<h2>EZ Coil Selection Procedure – 012</h2><p>This document defines the standardized procedure for transitioning engineered concepts into production-ready design packages. Its purpose is to ensure accuracy, consistency, and cross-functional alignment from initial project release through final build documentation.</p><ol><li><em>Purpose</em><ol type="a"><li>To train engineers on how to select EZ Coils.</li></ol></li><li><em>Scope</em><ol type="a"><li>EZ Coil Selection</li></ol></li><li><em>Responsibility</em><ol type="a"><li>Engineering</li></ol></li><li><em>References</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Definitions</em><ol type="a"><li>IDP – Integrated Desiccant Product</li><li>LLI – Long-Lead Items</li><li>DH – Dehumidifier</li><li>Takt Time – Cycle Time</li><li>Total Time – Total Project Duration</li></ol></li><li><em>Safety</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Procedure</em></li></ol><h3>Procedure Checklist</h3><ol><li><strong>Flow Diagram</strong><ol type="a"><li>Refer to flow diagram to know ambient conditions, air temperature, and volume.</li><li>ADD DIAGRAM HERE</li></ol></li><li><strong>Project Info</strong><ol type="a"><li>Open EZ Coil software</li><li>Right click on your name</li><li>Add project name (job number + customer name)</li><li>Quote to will always be Innovative Air Technologies</li><li>Ship to will also be Innovative Air Technologies</li><li>Save</li><li>New Job will populate down at the bottom</li><li>Right click on the job (new coil – select type of coil)</li><li>ADD SCREENSHOT HERE</li></ol></li><li><strong>Coil Selection</strong><ol type="a"><li>Right click on the project</li><li>New coil</li><li>Select type coil as per application</li><li>It will pop up new window for coil selection</li><li>Item number 1 (default)</li><li>Coil per bank 1 (default)</li><li>Keep tube geometry as default unless customer has unique requirement</li><li>Fin pattern waffle unless customer has unique requirement</li><li>Enter rows and fin density as auto select</li><li>Fin height and fin length to right velocity<ol><li>Example: fin height 10 x fin length 20 to get 600 CFM velocities</li><li>ENTER SCREENSHOT HERE</li></ol></li></ol></li><li><strong>Airside</strong><ol type="a"><li>Enter CFM as per flow diagram</li><li>Enter altitude in feet as per flow diagram</li><li>Run performance to verify FPM value</li><li>Check drawings<ol><li>ENTER SCREENSHOT HERE</li></ol></li><li>To calculate wet bulb temperature, use psychrometric chart from link: <a href="http://iatcalc.dehumidifiers.com/calculatorapp">http://iatcalc.dehumidifiers.com/calculatorapp</a></li><li>To get entering air wet bulb temperature value, enter the wet bulb and moisture value from process inlet (flow diagram)<ol><li>ENTER SCREENSHOT HERE</li></ol></li><li>To get leaving air wet bulb temperature value, enter wet bulb temperature and moisture value from process inlet (flow diagram)<ol><li>ENTER SCREENSHOT HERE</li></ol></li><li><strong>Internal Fluid</strong><ol><li>Use refrigerant as R404 unless customer has unique requirement (check PO to verify)</li><li>Liquid temperature 110f (default)</li><li>Evaporator temperature is typically minus 10 degrees of leaving dry air bulb temperature</li><li>Do not enter evaporator temperature over 40F as condenser manufactures max suction temperature is 40F</li><li>Keep leaving superheat as 6</li><li>Keep FPM between 400–480. DO NOT exceed 550 FPM.<ol><li>ENTER SCREENSHOT HERE</li></ol></li></ol></li><li><strong>Construction</strong><ol><li>If coil is front of the unit right hand coil and if coil is rear of the unit left hand</li><li>Select all inputs as per customer requirement<ol><li>ENTER SCREENSHOT HERE</li></ol></li></ol></li><li><strong>Special Option</strong><ol><li>Typical IAT Selections<ol><li>Stacked Flanges</li><li>Aux Side Conns (for hot gas)</li><li>TXV – Installed</li></ol></li><li>Select Special Options as per customer requirement<ol><li>Check PO to verify that if customer has any special options<ol><li>ENTER SCREENSHOT HERE</li></ol></li></ol></li></ol></li><li><strong>Drawing Creation</strong><ol><li>Click on run performance after getting correct velocity in FPM (in Airside section)</li><li>Check air pressure drop value</li><li>Suction velocity should be above 1000 FPM</li><li>Tube vapor velocity should be above 1000 FPM<ol><li>I reduced the number of feeds</li><li>I switched to rifled tubing.</li></ol></li></ol></li></ol></li></ol><h3>Drawing Optimization (refrigerate pressure drop)</h3><ul><li>If I get to 10 PSI, I try to increase the number of feeds, 2–8 is awesome.</li><li>The entire TXV, distributor and distributor tubes usually have 200 to 300 psig of pressure drop, sometimes higher. So, a couple of pounds more in the evaporator won&apos;t hurt the system a lot.</li><li>If it goes under 1 PSI, I try to reduce the feeds to raise it.</li><li>When you change the feeds, you must look at the right side of the drawing and see how many dropped tube you have.</li><li>I do not like more than 2x the rows dep dropped, MAX.</li><li>EZ-Coil lets you set the number of feeds but does not warn you when more than 2x rows depth are exceeded.</li></ul><p>Additional steps: verify leaving air temperature DB/WB, click on drawing tab, make sure we have enough clearance around the coil headers, make sure there are no dropped tubes in circuiting section. If any drop tubes then select rows and fin density manually in input section to get it down to Zero. In drawing inputs select ASC orientation to Right, ASC Extension to 10 and SL value to 6. Click on save coil and coil gets added in left section. Select the coil, right click and click on quotation. Customer information card gets opened. Click on same as customer quoted. Click add performances and add drawings. Click on submit and it will create all documents related to it.</p>', 59, TRUE, 6
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'engineering'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'New York Blower Selection Procedure – 013', 'new-york-blower-selection-procedure-013', '<h2>New York Blower Selection Procedure – 013</h2><p>This document defines the standardized procedure for transitioning engineered concepts into production-ready design packages.</p><ol><li><em>Purpose</em><ol type="a"><li>To train engineers on how to select New York Blowers</li></ol></li><li><em>Scope</em><ol type="a"><li>New York Blowers selection</li></ol></li><li><em>Responsibility</em><ol type="a"><li>Engineering</li></ol></li><li><em>References</em><ol type="a"><li><a href="https://apps.nyb.com/fantosize/ProductSelection.aspx">https://apps.nyb.com/fantosize/ProductSelection.aspx</a></li></ol></li><li><em>Definitions</em><ol type="a"><li>SP: ??</li><li>ESP: ??</li></ol></li><li><em>Safety</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Procedure</em></li></ol><h3>Procedure Checklist</h3><ol><li><strong>Selection of New York Blower</strong><ol type="a"><li>Open the submittal package</li><li>Review features and flow diagram</li><li>Open Static Pressure Calc Form</li><li>Update CFM for Process and React</li><li>List all process components and their estimated pressure drops found in their product data sheets<ol><li>Units are in inches water column (&apos;WC)</li><li>MERV 8 Filters are typically 1.0&apos; WC (dirty)</li><li>Desiccant wheel SP can be found on the flow diagram or in their data sheets</li></ol></li><li>Determine ESP<ol><li>ENTER SCREENSHOT HERE</li></ol></li></ol></li><li><strong>Product Selection</strong><ol type="a"><li>Go to New York Blower product selection</li><li>Anything above 3000 CFM, and not high pressure, and not plenum fan then select that to default to backward inclined SWSI square fan</li><li>Click on continue<ol><li>ENTER SCREENSHOT HERE</li></ol></li></ol></li><li><strong>Fan Characteristics/Operating Conditions</strong><ol type="a"><li>Go to fan characteristics/operation conditions</li><li>Fill details can be taken from flow diagram such as pressure (Cumulative pressure as calculated above) volume flow, altitude, operating temperature (Higher the temperature, lesser the dense air will be, fan has to work harder) which can be taken from flow diagram, operating temperature and maximum temperature will be the same.<ol><li>ENTER SCREENSHOT HERE</li></ol></li></ol></li><li><strong>Fan Attributes</strong><ol type="a"><li>Now fill Fan Attributes: Motor frequency can be taken from PO</li><li>Fill size, drive mode (Always direct)</li><li>Fan speed should always be less than 5000 RPM, around 3500 RPM</li><li>Ignore class</li><li>Wheel material is carbon steels<ol><li>Aluminum wheels can be selected for explosion proof applications or when carbon steel wheels are not available</li></ol></li><li>Arrangement is 4</li><li>Leave all fields blank as of now</li><li>Then, select and density mismatch popup will come</li><li>Click on YES (CHANGE)</li><li>We will get some of the results</li><li>We will try to get smallest size possible<ol><li>ENTER SCREENSHOT HERE</li></ol></li></ol></li><li><strong>Sound DB Standards for Reference</strong><ol type="a"><li>Preference is below 80 dB<ol><li>ENTER SCREENSHOT HERE</li></ol></li></ol></li><li><strong>Sound Policy and Operating Cost</strong><ol type="a"><li>Click on view, check sound policy and operating cost graphs</li><li>Click on find pressure, selected width aas 100% and refresh</li><li>This leads change in static pressure and power</li><li>Graph will update automatically<ol><li>ENTER SCREENSHOT HERE</li></ol></li><li>Select cover sheet, sound, curve, then generate<ol><li>ENTER SCREENSHOT HERE</li></ol></li></ol></li><li><strong>Drawing Generation</strong><ol type="a"><li>Click on Generate Drawing and select specifications as per below snap<ol><li>ENTER SCREENSHOT HERE</li></ol></li></ol></li></ol>', 60, TRUE, 5
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'engineering'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Condenser Selection Procedure – 017', 'condenser-selection-procedure-017', '<h2>Condenser Selection Procedure – 017</h2><p>This document defines the standardized procedure for transitioning engineered concepts into production-ready design packages.</p><ol><li><em>Purpose</em><ol type="a"><li>To train engineers on how to select condensing units for projects.</li></ol></li><li><em>Scope</em><ol type="a"><li>HeatCraft Condensing Units</li><li>KeepRite Condensing Units</li></ol></li><li><em>Responsibility</em><ol type="a"><li>Engineering</li></ol></li><li><em>References</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Definitions</em><ol type="a"><li>IDP – Integrated Desiccant Product</li><li>LLI – Long-Lead Items</li><li>DH – Dehumidifier</li><li>Variable Speed EC Motor: Is an electronic commutation motor that can control speed automatically and allows for more efficient control over the speed of the rotor.<ul><li>Benefits: Provides a dramatic improvement in stable head pressure and liquid temperature, Provides a significant reduction in fan motor power consumption, Provides a more stable system, Improves product integrity, Improves compressor durability, Reduces energy consumption</li><li>Disadvantages: Increased cost, Increased lead times</li></ul></li><li>Hot Gas Bypass: The discharge bypass valve is located in a branch line off the discharge line close to the compressor. The bypassed hot gas can enter the low side at the inlet of the evaporator or at the suction line. The hot gas bypass valve is adjustable to maintain the desired evaporating or suction pressure. Maintaining a constant evaporating pressure regulated by the modulating hot gas will allow for a constant coil temperature resulting in a constant room temperature regardless of room load.<ul><li>Bypass to inlet of the evaporator is the preferred method because the TXV will provide the correct amount of liquid refrigerant for desuperheating. In addition, the evaporator allows for proper mixing of liquid and hot gas ensuring dry super-heated refrigerant returns to the compressor.</li><li>Bypass to the suction line is used with long line runs and with multiple evaporators. The addition of a specific desuperheating TXV is required to prevent overloading (overheating) of the compressor due to high return gas temperatures caused by bypassed hot gas close to the compressor. A suction accumulator is also recommended, as this will ensure proper mixing of the hot gas and liquid refrigerant prior to it reaching the compressor.</li></ul></li></ol></li><li><em>Safety</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li></ol><h3>Condenser Selection</h3><h3>HeatCraft Condensing Units</h3><ol><li>Go to the HUB at <a href="https://hub.heatcraftrpd.com/">https://hub.heatcraftrpd.com/</a></li><li>If an account doesn&apos;t exist, please set up an account with a sales rep.</li><li>Once the account is setup, select Advanced Selection Assistant from the Quotes drop down list.<ol type="a"><li>Select air-cooled condensers from the Category drop down list.</li><li>Is HP – known select type, if not, select NO PREFERENCE.</li><li>In Factory Options, select the following features:<ul><li>Fixed Speed or Variable Speed Fans<ul><li>Select Fixed Speed on low cost units when efficiency isn&apos;t as important.</li><li>Select Variable Speed when customer is requesting increased performance (See definitions for pros and cons)</li></ul></li><li>Suction Line Options<ul><li>Filter and Accumulator required on all Hot Gas to Evap selections</li><li>Receiver Options<ul><li>Add low ambient kits in cold environments</li><li>Add oversized receivers when refrigerant is greater than what a standard receiver can hold. Use refrigerator calculator to determine total refrigerant of system.</li></ul></li></ul></li><li>Add Custom Note<ul><li>Hot gas bypass to evaporator is preferred Hot gas bypass method.</li><li>Hot gas bypass to suction is another method, but not preferred.</li><li>Add boil out accumulator to minimize the risk of liquid coming back through to the compressor.<ul><li>Precooling: both injectors and evap and cond fan motor speed control and low ambient control</li><li>Postcooling: hot gas to evap and low ambient</li><li>Variable speed compressor if an option, or digital scrolls</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul></li></ol></li></ol>', 61, TRUE, 6
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'engineering'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Actuator Selection Procedure – 019', 'actuator-selection-procedure-019', '<h2>Actuator Selection Procedure – 019</h2><p>This document defines the standardized procedure for transitioning engineered concepts into production-ready design packages.</p><ol><li><em>Purpose</em><ol type="a"><li>To train engineers on how to select actuators.</li></ol></li><li><em>Scope</em><ol type="a"><li>Damper Actuators</li></ol></li><li><em>Responsibility</em><ol type="a"><li>Engineering</li><li>Sales</li></ol></li><li><em>References</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Definitions</em><ol type="a"><li>SP</li><li>ESP</li></ol></li><li><em>Safety</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Procedure</em></li></ol><h3>Procedure Checklist</h3><ol><li><strong>Selection of Actuators for Dampers</strong><ol type="a"><li>Calculate Torque of Damper (in lbs)<ol><li>Use Excel Spreadsheet in Damper Folder<ol><li>Enter CFM, W, H, in lb is calculated</li></ol></li></ol></li><li>Determine Voltage<ol><li>Open electrical drawings and find actuator. Voltage is called out at the top of the drawing.</li></ol></li><li>Select control type.<ol><li>On/Off, Floating, Modulating, MFT</li><li>Refer to features on submittal page for type or ask sales or electrical engineering</li><li>If a customer is needing feedback from the actuator, select Auxiliary Switch selection. 1x SPDT</li></ol></li></ol></li></ol>', 62, TRUE, 3
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'engineering'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Spare Parts Procedure – 020', 'spare-parts-procedure-020', '<h2>Spare Parts Procedure – 020</h2><p>This document defines the standardized procedure for transitioning engineered concepts into production-ready design packages.</p><ol><li><em>Purpose</em><ol type="a"><li>To train IAT members on how to determine spare parts selection.</li></ol></li><li><em>Scope</em><ol type="a"><li>Spare parts for all dehumidifier product lines.</li></ol></li><li><em>Responsibility</em><ol type="a"><li>Engineering</li></ol></li><li><em>References</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Definitions</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Safety</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Procedure</em></li></ol><h3>Procedure Checklist</h3><ol><li><strong>Determine whether a part is critical, non-critical, or non-spare part.</strong><ol type="a"><li>Ask the following question to determine if a part is a critical spare part:<ol><li>Are there any specific components that have longer lead times for procurement (&gt;3weeks) or are more challenging to source that are essential to the systems operation?</li><li>Are there components that require specialized calibration or adjustment during installation, and should they be included in the spare parts list? (Example: PLC, HMI, PXR3 controllers)</li><li>Is the part essential for the unit&apos;s functionality and cannot be easily repaired or replaced on-site during an emergency? (Example: Essential = Heater, Non-Essential: Lights, Mini Helic Gauge)<ol><li>If the answer to any of the previous questions is YES, it should be considered a critical spare part.</li></ol></li></ol></li><li>Then ask the following questions to determine if the remaining parts are non-critical spare part:<ol><li>Will the part potentially need to be replaced within the next 5 year? (Example: Filters)</li><li>Is part more prone to failure?<ol><li>If the answer to any of the previous questions is yes, it should be considered a non-critical spare part.</li></ol></li><li>All other remaining parts are to be considered non-spare parts. (Example: Control Box, Framing)</li></ol></li></ol></li><li><strong>Identify part classification on BOM &ldquo;SPARE&rdquo; column</strong><ol type="a"><li>Mark &lsquo;X&rsquo; for all critical spare parts</li><li>Mark &lsquo;SP&rsquo; for all non-critical spare parts</li><li>Leave blank all non-spare parts</li></ol></li><li><strong>Process Complete</strong></li></ol>', 63, TRUE, 4
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'engineering'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'TigerLink Installation Procedure – 021', 'tigerlink-installation-procedure-021', '<h2>TigerLink Installation Procedure – 021</h2><p>This document defines the standardized procedure for transitioning engineered concepts into production-ready design packages.</p><h3>Setup and Installation</h3><ol><li>Download the latest version of TigerLink6 from the TigerStop website (or use link below): <a href="https://www.tigerstop.com/download/tigerlink-6-102-download/?wppdmdl=11305&amp;refresh=60f58a3383b051626704435">https://www.tigerstop.com/download/tigerlink-6-102-download/</a></li><li>Unzip the TigerLink6 Installation File (TigerLink6.msi)</li><li>Run TigerLink6.msi</li><li>Click &lsquo;Install&rsquo; and press &lsquo;Finish&rsquo;</li><li>During installation, TigerLink6 creates a TigerLink folder on the desktop. Inside, there&apos;s a separate folder for every TigerStop product&apos;s serial number that is connected and a folder named &lsquo;Global&rsquo;</li></ol><h3>Creating CSV file</h3><ol><li>Open the CutList xls file created from the SW Weldment BOM</li><li>Copy Columns: ITEM NO, QTY, DESCRIPTION, LENGTH L(IN)</li><li>Open a New Excel Sheet and Paste Special (Values Only)</li><li>Specific order and format are required for the Tiger file to generate correctly<ol type="a"><li>Swap Length and L (IN) columns</li><li>Rename LENGTH to L (MM) and L (IN) to LENGTH</li></ol></li><li>New Column Order: ITEM NO, QTY, DESCRIPTION, LENGTH, L (MM)<ol type="a"><li>Headings (Left Aligned), Part Descriptions (Left Aligned), and Numbers (Right Aligned)</li></ol></li><li>Save As .csv file format &ldquo;CSV UTF-8&rdquo;</li></ol><h3>Creating Tiger Files</h3><ol><li>Open &ldquo;TigerLink&rdquo; folder on desktop</li><li>Open &ldquo;Global&rdquo; folder</li><li>Copy &ldquo;CutList&rdquo;.csv file and paste into &ldquo;Global&rdquo; folder</li><li>Tiger files will automatically generate</li></ol><h3>Additional Items</h3><ol><li>To access the &lsquo;cutlistlinks.xml&rsquo; file location<ol type="a"><li>Open Windows File Explorer and type %appdata% into the address bar</li><li>Press &ldquo;Enter&rdquo; and the address bar will change to C:\Users\Admin\AppData\Roaming</li><li>Open the &ldquo;TigerLink&rdquo; folder to access file</li></ol></li><li>To use the current .csv files on a new computer, the &ldquo;cutlistlinks.xml&rdquo; file will need to be copied<ol type="a"><li>Open the &ldquo;%appdata%&rdquo; folder. Inside of that is the &ldquo;cutlistlinks.xml&rdquo; file.</li><li>After TigerLink has been installed on the new computer, exit out of TigerLink</li><li>Copy the current .xml file from the old computer into the new computer &ldquo;%appdata%&rdquo; folder and restart TigerLink.</li></ol></li></ol>', 64, TRUE, 4
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'engineering'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Continuous Improvement Procedure – 022', 'continuous-improvement-procedure-022', '<h2>Continuous Improvement Procedure – 022</h2><p>This document defines the standardized procedure for transitioning engineered concepts into production-ready design packages.</p><ol><li><em>Purpose</em><ol type="a"><li>To train IAT members on how to log and create corrective actions for design and manufacturing feedback.</li></ol></li><li><em>Scope</em><ol type="a"><li>Any questions that relate to the design, construction, or performance of a system. Including but not limited to general feedback, errors, or design improvements.</li></ol></li><li><em>Responsibility</em><ol type="a"><li>Engineering and Manufacturing</li></ol></li><li><em>References</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Definitions</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Safety</em><ol type="a"><li>N/A</li></ol></li><li><em>Procedure</em></li></ol><h3>Procedure Checklist</h3><ol><li><strong>Go to Master Workbook (Master 7.20.22) and open the Cont Improvement Worksheet</strong></li><li>Whenever feedback is shared with Engineering on anything related to the design or manufacturing of our systems complete an entry for that item.</li><li><strong>Types of entries are classified as the following:</strong><ol type="a"><li><strong>Pre-Production</strong>: Prior to release from engineering to production</li><li><strong>In-Design</strong>: During the build of a unit</li><li><strong>Post Production</strong>: Meeting held to review unit prior to shipment</li><li><strong>Customer</strong>: Feedback from a customer</li><li><strong>Continuous Improvement</strong>: General feedback/requests shared with engineering for continuous improvement</li></ol></li></ol>', 65, TRUE, 4
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'engineering'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Submittal Package Creation Checklist', 'submittal-package-creation-checklist', '<h2>Submittal Package Creation Checklist</h2><p>This is a submittal package verification checklist used to ensure all engineering, construction, and documentation details are accurate before a unit is released to the customer. It walks through key design confirmations, component selections, compliance checks, and required supporting documents to reduce errors and rework. The checklist serves as a final quality-control step to confirm the package is complete, coordinated, and ready for submission.</p><h3>Submittal Package Checklist Questions</h3><ul><li>Has the latest submittal package been copied?</li><li>Has the revision comments section been updated?</li><li>Is the installation checklist correct?</li><li>Is the features page correct?</li></ul><hr><h3>Unit Construction / Component Checks</h3><ul><li>Does the Unit Construction match the Sales Order?</li><li>Verify Insulation Selection</li><li>Single or Double Wall Construction</li><li>Any special construction requests?</li><li>Is there a baseframe?</li><li>Do fan selections match the cutsheets?</li><li>Verify static pressure calculations</li><li>Verify filter types</li><li>Verify damper types and control</li><li>Verify react heater size and type</li><li>Verify cooling coil selections and features</li><li>Verify process heater size and type</li><li>Verify control box construction &amp; NEMA rating</li><li>Verify electrical standards &amp; options</li><li>Verify control package</li><li>Is FAT required?</li><li>Is start-up required?</li><li>Standard warranty or special?</li></ul><hr><h3>Final Package Validation</h3><ul><li>Does the ASHRAE weather report match the flow diagram conditions?</li><li>Does the OA dimensions on the unit outline meet the sizing restrictions?</li><li>Is a base frame drawing required?</li><li>Are construction details required?</li><li>Has the electrical drawings submittal cross check been completed?</li><li>Have all cutsheets for the major components been created and added?</li><li>Are the terms and conditions the latest revision?</li></ul>', 66, TRUE, 4
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'technical-training' AND m.slug = 'engineering'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
